Overview:
This lab demonstrates analysis of Linux authentication logs to identify failed login attempts, privilege escalation activity, and potential brute-force behaviour. The objective was to practise log-based detection techniques commonly used by SOC analysts and system administrators.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Environment:
Host Platform: VirtualBox
Operating System: Ubuntu Linux
Log Sources:
/var/log/auth.log
journalctl
Tools Used:
grep
journalctl
Linux command-line utilities
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Objectives:
Analyse Linux authentication logs for security-relevant events
Identify failed login attempts and sudo usage
Understand indicators of brute-force or suspicious activity
Apply SOC-style log investigation techniques
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Methodology:
An Ubuntu Linux virtual machine was configured and updated.
Authentication logs were analysed using the following commands:
sudo less /var/log/auth.log
Failed login attempts were identified using keyword filtering:
sudo grep "Failed password" /var/log/auth.log
Privilege escalation activity was analysed by reviewing sudo events:
sudo grep "sudo" /var/log/auth.log
System-wide authentication events were reviewed using journalctl:
journalctl -xe
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Analysis & Findings:
Failed Authentication Attempts
Observed failed login attempts recorded in auth.log.
Identified timestamps, usernames, and source processes associated with failed authentication.
Confirmed normal vs abnormal login behaviour patterns.
Privilege Escalation Monitoring
Analysed sudo usage to identify when elevated privileges were requested.
Confirmed legitimate user activity versus potential misuse scenarios.
Log Structure & Event Context
Gained understanding of log entry structure, including timestamps, services, and severity.
Correlated multiple log entries to understand event sequences.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Security Relevance:
Authentication logs are a critical data source for detecting:
Brute-force login attempts
Unauthorised access attempts
Misuse of administrative privileges
This lab demonstrates foundational log analysis skills required for SOC Level 1 and junior security analyst roles.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Conclusion:
The lab successfully demonstrated the ability to analyse Linux authentication logs to detect security-relevant events. By identifying failed login attempts and monitoring privilege escalation activity, this exercise reflects real-world SOC and blue-team monitoring workflows.
